                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d758">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/3142: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Crane</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-12-16T17:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 16, 1920—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 17—1:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>441. Your 352, December 3, 5 p.m. Various Legations have replied severally to
                    Foreign Office. American, British, Japanese and French banks, latter “Indo
                    Chine”, have been approached by the Chinese Government for loan as forecasted in
                    note of Foreign Office. Amount to be $4,000,000.</p>
                <p>Four Legations have suggested to dean calling meeting of the corps [to] discuss
                    question and ascertaining from the Chinese Government when approval of
                    Governments concerned has been given and Inspector General [of] Customs has
                    received instructions to levy tax.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Crane</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
